{
  "answer": "Several works in the corpus offer explicit or sustained doctrines of selfhood:\n\n1. **Gaṇapatitattva** (`unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136`, ch.1) — The most systematic self-doctrine in the corpus. It enumerates \"The Five Selves\": the Self, the Supreme Self, the Inner Self, the Non-Self, and the Void-Self. It identifies the Self as \"Self-born and by itself worshipped\" and as the true deity for sages, while the external liṅga is merely a symbol.\n\n2. **San Hyan Tattvajnana** (`unknown-san-hyan-tattvajnana-1f29bd`, ch.1) — A Kawi philosophical text with a detailed doctrine of the Divine Ātmā. It classifies Ātmikatattva (Self-principle) as one of three divisions of Śivatattva, and traces the ātmā's states (waking, dreaming, deep sleep, turīya), transmigrations driven by triguṇa, and eventual liberation (mokṣa).\n\n3. **Vrhaspatitattva** (`unknown-vrhaspatitattva-b60b28`, ch.1) — Another Kawi text with an extended doctrine of the ātmā as the lord who uses the ten sense organs as instruments. It discusses ātmā viparīta (distorted/inverted self), the soul's attachment to sensual enjoyment, and the path to liberation.\n\n4. **Yājñavalkya Smṛti** (`unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6`, ch.3) — Provides a Sanskrit Vedāntic doctrine: individual souls emerge from the Supreme Self like sparks from iron (Yj_3.67); the practitioner must \"see the subtle Self situated in himself through the yoga of meditation\" (Yj_3.64); and the Puruṣa becomes individual soul through delusion, desire, aversion, and karma (Yj_3.125).\n\n5. **Allama Iqbal — Bang-E-Dara Parts 1, 2, and 3** (`allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c`, `allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c`, `allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8`) — Iqbal's philosophy of khudi (selfhood/ego) runs throughout all three parts. Part 1 ch.9 urges seeking one's own true path rather than blind imitation; Part 2 ch.23 (\"Swami Ram Tirath\") refers to shattering the idol of the Self through Love. The collection as a whole articulates individual selfhood as the foundation of spiritual and civilizational renewal.\n\n6. **San Hyan Mahajnana** (`unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531`, ch.1) — A Kawi text that addresses the body of the ātmā (the Self) as the dwelling place of the divine Lord; it poses questions about what sleeps, wakes, and wanders within the body, elaborating a doctrine of the self in relation to the divine.\n\n7. **Nyaya Tilakam Pandulipi** (`unknown-nyaya-tilakam-pandulipi-bookny`, ch.5) — Within the Nyaya ontological framework, Self is listed as one of nine substances. It distinguishes atomic individual selves from the all-pervading Self of Ishvara (the supreme being), providing a metaphysical doctrine of selfhood.\n\n8. **Manusmṛti** (`unknown-manusmrti-347b76`, ch.1) — Contains a cosmological doctrine in which the divine Self-existent One manifests the universe; from himself he produces ego (ahaṃkāra) and the great soul; \"He who is... the soul of all beings\" (Mn_1.7). This frames a doctrine of the universal self as cosmological ground.\n\nThe Urdu ghazal works (Diwan-E-Ghalib, Diwan-E-Zauq) engage self-related themes through be-khudi (ecstatic self-loss) but offer mystical poetics rather than systematic doctrines.",
